# Architecture Decisions

## Decision 1: Modules as a layer above collections
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The old schema had flat collections (rms_timesheet, hrms_leave_data) without grouping. The new schema needs to organize them.
**Old approach:** Single flat `collections` table with department as a grouping hint.
**New approach:** `dpah_modules` table sits above `dpah_collections`. Each collection belongs to exactly one module via `module_id`.
**Why this is better:** Modules provide a clean UI grouping (RMS tiles, HRMS tiles) while collections represent the actual data sources. Modules are stable business domains; collections may change frequently.
**Trade-offs:** Extra JOIN when querying — but this is a one-time cost per endpoint.
**Industry pattern reference:** Domain-driven design — bounded contexts (modules) vs. data sources (collections).
**Where it lives in code:** `app/models/db_schema.py` (Module, Collection); `scripts/seed_dpah_tables.py` (seed data).

## Decision 2: Group vs. role: orthogonal dimensions
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** Users need both organizational grouping (what modules are visible) and permission-based filtering (what agents/personas within those modules).
**Old approach:** Roles directly mapped to collections via `role_collection_access`. A single dimension.
**New approach:** `group_idx` (from resources) controls module-level visibility. `dpah_role_agent_access` combines `role_id + group_id + agent_id` for fine-grained access. Two independent axes that intersect.
**Why this is better:** Changing a role doesn't break module visibility. Adding a new module only requires updating `dpah_module_usergroups`, not every role-agent mapping.
**Trade-offs:** Slightly more complex query logic — but matches real-world org charts (department + job level).
**Industry pattern reference:** RBAC + ABAC hybrid — groups as organizational units (ABAC), roles as permission sets (RBAC).
**Where it lives in code:** `app/controllers/auth_controller.py` (build_user_context_by_empno).

## Decision 3: Composite-key-as-access-control (no row = no access)
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** Need to express "a role in a group can access this agent."
**Old approach:** `role_agent_access` with PK (role_id, agent_id) — group was not part of access.
**New approach:** `dpah_role_agent_access` with composite PK (role_id, group_id, agent_id). No row means no access. The absence of a row is itself the permission model.
**Why this is better:** Group-based access is explicit. If a role is not assigned to a group, there's no way to accidentally inherit access.
**Trade-offs:** More rows needed for roles that span multiple groups, but this is expected for admin-like roles.
**Industry pattern reference:** Zero-trust access control — deny by default, explicit grants only.
**Where it lives in code:** `app/models/db_schema.py` (RoleAgentAccess); `scripts/seed_dpah_tables.py`.

## Decision 4: Lean JWT vs. fat JWT
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The old JWT carried the full permission tree (allowed_agents, collections, collection_agents). This made tokens large, hard to update in real-time, and created stale permissions.
**Old approach:** Fat JWT with `allowed_agents`, `collections`, `collection_agents` embedded.
**New approach:** JWT carries only identity: `sub`, `name`, `email`, `dept`, `group_idx`, `role_ids`, `role_names`, `hierarchy`. Permissions are looked up from the DB on every API call.
**Why this is better:** Tokens are small, cheap to encode/decode. Permissions are always fresh from the DB. No need to re-issue tokens after permission changes.
**Trade-offs:** Every protected endpoint needs a DB query instead of checking JWT claims. This is acceptable given the per-request lookup pattern.
**Industry pattern reference:** Auth0 / Firebase practice — JWT for identity, session/DB for permissions.
**Where it lives in code:** `app/core/security.py` (create_access_token); `app/routes/auth_route.py` (login response).

## Decision 5: localStorage access tree is cosmetic only
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The frontend needs to know which tiles (modules) and agents to show the user.
**Old approach:** Access tree came from the JWT, so the frontend was always up to date but had a large token.
**New approach:** Login returns the access_tree in the response body. The frontend caches it in localStorage for rendering. The tree is refreshed via `GET /me/access` when needed.
**Why this is better:** The access_tree is no longer tied to the JWT. The frontend can re-fetch it independently without re-authenticating.
**Trade-offs:** Brief stale state possible between permission changes and the next `/me/access` call. Acceptable because admin actions will trigger a frontend refresh.
**Industry pattern reference:** Client-side routing with server-synced state (React Router + React Query pattern).
**Where it lives in code:** `app/routes/auth_route.py` (login returns access_tree); new endpoint `/me/access`.

## Decision 6: DB-checked permissions with future caching
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** Every protected API call must verify the user can access the requested agent.
**Old approach:** Permissions were trusted from the JWT (no re-check on protected endpoints).
**New approach:** `check_agent_access()` does a JOIN query on every protected endpoint. This is the single source of truth. Task 3 will add Redis/in-memory caching.
**Why this is better:** Even if the JWT is compromised or stale, the DB check prevents unauthorized access. Consistent security model.
**Trade-offs:** Extra DB round-trip per protected endpoint. Caching (Task 3) will mitigate this. The query is simple (single JOIN with indexed PK).
**Industry pattern reference:** "Check at the gateway" / microgateway pattern — always verify at the service boundary.
**Where it lives in code:** `app/controllers/auth_controller.py` (check_agent_access).

## Decision 7: Persona parsed from agent_name (no separate column)
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The seeded agents have names like "RMS_TIMESHEET_CREATOR". The persona (CREATOR/REVIEWER/APPROVER) is encoded in the name suffix.
**Old approach:** Separate `persona` column required in the database.
**New approach:** No persona column. Persona is extracted by splitting agent_name on "_" and taking the last segment, uppercased.
**Why this is better:** Saves a column, avoids DB migration. The naming convention is self-documenting.
**Trade-offs:** Parsing overhead on every access_tree build. Parsing is brittle if naming conventions change. Acceptable because agent names are stable (created by seed, not user input).
**Industry pattern reference:** Self-describing identifiers / convention-over-configuration.
**Where it lives in code:** `app/controllers/auth_controller.py` (persona parsing in build_user_context_by_empno).

## Decision 8: One workflow per module; collection chosen via intent
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** Each module has its own LangGraph workflow. The user sends a message — the system needs to decide which collection and persona to route to.
**Old approach:** User explicitly selected collection_name + agent_role in the chat request.
**New approach:** User sends a free-text message. The frontend shows available collections/personas from the access_tree. The system infers the intent (collection + persona) from the message context.
**Why this is better:** Better UX — user doesn't need to know the exact collection name. The system infers the right workflow.
**Trade-offs:** Requires an intent classifier (LLM-based). Adds latency to the first message of a chat.
**Industry pattern reference:** Intent-based routing in conversational AI (Dialogflow, Lex).
**Where it lives in code:** To be implemented in Task 4 (workflows).

## Decision 9: Single LLM intent classifier returning collection + persona
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** When a user sends a message, the system needs to determine which collection and persona to use.
**Old approach:** Multiple classifiers or manual selection.
**New approach:** One LLM call that returns `{collection_name: str, persona: str}`. The persona comes from the access_tree (what the user is allowed), the collection is inferred from the message content.
**Why this is better:** Single LLM call is simpler than multiple parallel calls. Persona is constrained by what the user can actually access.
**Trade-offs:** One LLM call per message adds ~1-2s latency. Acceptable for conversational AI.
**Industry pattern reference:** Single-prompt routing (LangChain Router).
**Where it lives in code:** To be implemented in Task 4 (workflows).

## Decision 10: Same routes, different ports (no V2 versioning)
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The old project runs on a different port but uses the same API routes. The new RBAC schema is being deployed alongside.
**Old approach:** Versioned APIs (/api/v1, /api/v2).
**New approach:** Same routes, different ports. The new backend runs on the same port but with updated models. The old project stays on its port unchanged.
**Why this is better:** No URL changes needed for frontend or API consumers. The database table prefix (`dpah_`) isolates new data from old.
**Trade-offs:** Two running services need to be managed. But deployment is simpler — no route migration.
**Industry pattern reference:** Parallel deployment / blue-green deployment without route versioning.
**Where it lives in code:** `main.py` (port 5970); `app/core/config.py` (DB connection).

## Decision 11: dpah_ prefix for new tables
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** The new RBAC tables live in the same database (`dpintranet`) as old tables, but must not interfere.
**Old approach:** New tables would share the existing naming convention (roles, collections, agents).
**New approach:** All new tables get the `dpah_` prefix: `dpah_roles`, `dpah_collections`, `dpah_agents`, etc. Old tables (`roles`, `collections`, `agents`, `role_collection_access`) are untouched.
**Why this is better:** Clear visual distinction. Safe to keep old tables around for backward compatibility. Easy to identify which tables are managed by this project.
**Trade-offs:** Slightly longer table names in queries. The `dpah_` prefix is project-specific, not a universal convention.
**Industry pattern reference:** Namespace prefixing (Kubernetes `app.kubernetes.io/` labels).
**Where it lives in code:** `app/models/db_schema.py` (`__tablename__` values).

## Decision 12: Minimal-disturbance principle for refactoring
**Date:** 2026-05-20
**Context:** This is a backend refactor of the auth flow. Changing too many files at once creates high risk.
**Old approach:** Full rewrite of all auth-related files simultaneously, touching controllers, routes, models, schemas.
**New approach:** Only touch the minimum set of files needed for each task. Leave chat_controller, rag_controller, chat_route, agent_route, workflows, forms, services, utils untouched. Add new endpoints (`/me/access`) instead of replacing old ones immediately.
**Why this is better:** Each task can be independently verified. Rolling back is easy (just revert one file). No unexpected breakage in unrelated parts of the system.
**Trade-offs:** Some dead code (old RoleCollectionAccess references) persists until explicitly cleaned up. But this is intentional — cleanup in later tasks.
**Industry pattern reference:** Strangler fig pattern — incrementally replace old system without big-bang rewrite.
**Where it lives in code:** Every task file. The `DO NOT TOUCH` sections in each task spec enforce this.
